Author: Robert C. Martin
Bookinformation: A guide on how to write clear, readable, and maintainable computer code, emphasizing best practices and principles for software craftsmanship.

Author: Andrew Hunt
Bookinformation: Offers advice and philosophy on how to be a more effective, productive, and reliable programmer in the modern software landscape.

Author: Erich Gamma
Bookinformation: A foundational text (the "Gang of Four" book) that catalogs reusable object-oriented software design solutions to common problems.

Author: Thomas H. Cormen
Bookinformation: A comprehensive and widely used textbook covering the fundamentals of algorithms and data structures, known by the initials "CLRS."

Author: Stuart Russell
Bookinformation: A standard, comprehensive textbook on the theory and practice of modern AI, covering topics from search algorithms to machine learning.

Author: Steve McConnell
Bookinformation: A practical handbook detailing software construction techniques, focusing on the art and science of coding, debugging, and systematic testing.

Author: Martin Fowler
Bookinformation: Defines and explains the process of restructuring existing computer code without changing its external behavior to improve design and quality.

Author: Eric Freeman
Bookinformation: A visually rich guide using brain-friendly learning techniques to teach fundamental software design patterns and object-oriented principles.

Author: Kyle Simpson
Bookinformation: A series of short books diving deep into the core mechanisms of the JavaScript language to help developers master its subtle parts.

Author: Frederick P. Brooks Jr.
Bookinformation: An influential essay on software project management, famously arguing that "adding more people to a late project only makes it later."

Author: Carl Sagan
Bookinformation: Carl Sagan's exploration of astronomy, science, civilization, and the universe, tied to his legendary 1980 television series.

Author: Stephen Hawking
Bookinformation: Stephen Hawking's accessible attempt to explain complex cosmological concepts like the Big Bang, black holes, and the nature of time.

Author: Richard Dawkins
Bookinformation: Proposes the gene's eye view of evolution, arguing that natural selection works primarily at the level of the gene, not the individual.

Author: Rachel Carson
Bookinformation: Rachel Carson's groundbreaking work that exposed the dangers of pesticides, helping to launch the modern environmental movement.

Author: Charles Darwin
Bookinformation: Charles Darwin's foundational work in evolutionary biology, introducing the theory of evolution by natural selection.

Author: Jared Diamond
Bookinformation: Explores why history unfolded differently for different peoples by examining environmental and geographical factors rather than racial ones.

Author: Yuval Noah Harari
Bookinformation: A global history of humankind, tracing the development of our species from early humans to the cognitive, agricultural, and scientific revolutions.

Author: Daniel Kahneman
Bookinformation: Explores the two systems that drive the way we think—System 1 (fast, intuitive) and System 2 (slow, logical)—and the cognitive biases that result.

Author: Niccolo Machiavelli
Bookinformation: Niccolò Machiavelli's political treatise offering practical, often ruthless, advice on how a ruler can acquire and maintain political power.

Author: Thomas Piketty
Bookinformation: Karl Marx's critical analysis of political economy, focusing on capitalism, its internal dynamics, and historical development.

Author: James Stewart
Bookinformation: A classic and rigorous textbook on the foundational concepts of Calculus, often referring to advanced texts like Michael Spivak's.

Author: Sheldon Axler
Bookinformation: A textbook that focuses on the conceptual understanding of linear algebra, organizing the material around operators rather than determinants.

Author: Trevor Hastie
Bookinformation: A textbook, often An Introduction to Statistical Learning, covering statistical methods for machine learning and data analysis.

Author: Kenneth Rosen
Bookinformation: A comprehensive textbook covering the core concepts of mathematics relevant to computer science, such as logic, set theory, and graph theory.

Author: Euclid
Bookinformation: A collection of 13 books written around 300 BC that forms the foundational text of geometry and rigorous mathematical proof.

Author: William Strunk Jr.
Bookinformation: A highly influential, concise American guide to English usage, writing style, and composition by Strunk and White.

Author: William Zinsser
Bookinformation: William Zinsser's classic guide to non-fiction writing, emphasizing clarity, simplicity, and warmth in all forms of writing.

Author: Anne Lamott
Bookinformation: Anne Lamott's humorous and honest instruction book offering advice on the writing process and the creative life, encouraging incremental progress.

Author: Lynne Truss
Bookinformation: A popular and humorous guide to proper punctuation, fiercely advocating for its strict adherence in English writing.

Author: Bill Bryson
Bookinformation: Bill Bryson's lively and entertaining history and explanation of the English language, tracing its evolution and peculiarities.

Author: E.H. Gombrich
Bookinformation: E.H. Gombrich's survey of art history from prehistoric times to the modern era, known for its accessible approach to visual culture.

Author: John Berger
Bookinformation: John Berger's influential book exploring the hidden ideologies in visual images and how we interpret art, often questioning traditional aesthetic theories.

Author: Don Norman
Bookinformation: Don Norman's essential book on design principles, focusing on how everyday objects should be designed for usability and comprehension.

Author: Josef Albers
Bookinformation: Josef Albers's seminal work presenting his study of color behavior and perception through experience and experimentation.

Author: Ellen Lupton
Bookinformation: A practical and comprehensive guide to typography, covering its history, fundamental principles, and professional application in design.

Author: James Clear
Bookinformation: A guide by James Clear on how to build good habits and break bad ones through small, incremental changes using four simple laws.

Author: Cal Newport
Bookinformation: Cal Newport's argument for the ability to focus without distraction on a cognitively demanding task and how to cultivate this valuable skill.

Author: Simon Sinek
Bookinformation: Simon Sinek's book proposing that inspiring leaders and organizations all start with a clear understanding of why they do what they do (The Golden Circle).

Author: Jim Collins
Bookinformation: Jim Collins's business book investigating how companies transition from being merely "good" to achieving sustained "great" results.

Author: Peter Thiel
Bookinformation: Peter Thiel's book on building startups and the future of innovation, arguing that true progress comes from creating new things (going from 0 to 1).

Author: Eric Ries
Bookinformation: Eric Ries's approach to creating startups and launching products, emphasizing rapid iteration, validated learning, and the MVP (Minimum Viable Product).

Author: Gayle Laakmann McDowell
Bookinformation: A comprehensive guide providing programming interview questions and solutions for software developers to prepare for technical job interviews.

Author: Harold Abelson
Bookinformation: A classic computer science textbook, SICP, using Lisp/Scheme to introduce fundamental concepts of programming and computation.

Author: Abraham Silberschatz
Bookinformation: A comprehensive and widely used textbook covering the design and implementation of operating systems, including processes, memory, and storage.

Author: James Kurose
Bookinformation: A top-down approach textbook detailing the principles and technologies of computer networks, starting from the application layer.

Author: Abraham Silberschatz
Bookinformation: A standard textbook on the fundamental concepts of database management systems, including design, query languages, and transaction processing.

Author: Alfred V. Aho
Bookinformation: The textbook Compilers: Principles, Techniques, and Tools, affectionately known as the "Dragon Book," covering compiler design.

Author: John L. Hennessy
Bookinformation: A quantitative approach to computer architecture and design, focusing on measuring, analyzing, and improving performance.

Author: Michael Negnevitsky
Bookinformation: A general text on AI, often referring to Artificial Intelligence: A Guide to Intelligent Systems by Michael Negnevitsky.

Author: Eric Matthes
Bookinformation: A fast-paced, practical introduction to programming with Python, focusing on hands-on projects and solving real-world problems.
